{
  "doc_id": "17812",
  "text": "The corpus callosum connects the left and right cerebral hemispheres and is the largest fibre bundle of the human brain. It is divided into an anterior portion (genu) connecting the prefrontal and orbitofrontal regions, a central part (body) connecting precentral frontal regions and parietal lobes, and a posterior portion connecting the occipital lobes (splenium) and temporal lobes (tapetum). The corpus callosum allows information transfer between hemispheres and is involved in several motor, perceptual and cognitive functions. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] The fibre bundles belonging to the central part of the corpus callosum recognized by the present study were the only region in the left hemisphere found by meta-analysis to have decreased fractional anisotropy. This may suggest a role for functional impairment of frontal lobe information transfer between hemispheres.",
